sentences: Hugh Wiley Hitchcock (September 28, 1923 in Detroit, Michigan – December 5, 2007 in New York, New York) was an American musicologist.
Hugh Wiley Hitchcock (September 28, 1923 in Detroit, Michigan – December 5, 2007 in New York, New York) was an American musicologist.
He is best known for founding the Institute for Studies in American Music at Brooklyn College of the City University of New York in 1971.
Hitchcock received a B.A. degree from Dartmouth College in 1944 and an M.A. from the University of Michigan in 1948.
Hitchcock received a B.A. degree from Dartmouth College in 1944 and an M.A. from the University of Michigan in 1948.
After study under Nadia Boulanger in Paris, he earned his Ph.D. at the University of Michigan in 1954.
He taught there from 1950 to 1961 and then at Hunter College from 1961 to 1971.
He taught there from 1950 to 1961 and then at Hunter College from 1961 to 1971.
He taught in the CUNY system until 1993, when he retired.
He served as president of the Music Library Association, 1966–1967, the Charles Ives Society, 1973–1993, and the American Musicological Society, 1990–1992.
